<br>
You must look after the health of your party of course as usual, but as a Cleric you should also make hotkeys to quickly target the Main Assist of the raid, and the Secondary Assist. Even though you are not the Cleric in their party, you should keep an eye on their health, and if needed assist the Cleric in that group with healing. To try and click the MA and/or SA in the flurry of raid melee combat is not an easy task, while a hotkey is fail-safe if you are within range.<br>
<br>
Also, make a hotkey to automatically ask the Enchanter assigned to this task to refresh Clarity (II) when it fades, to avoid having to type it again and again.<br>
<br>
As Eannyil said, bring Peridots and Jaspers. Most will ask you to bring one or two stacks of each (you will need them, trust me). Usually raid leaders will either give you these Symbol components or - more common - give out money items looted during the raid to compensate Clerics and Enchanters (Rune spells) for the gems they used up, before dsitributing the remaining items over the entire raid party (you included). Note that there are some exceptions, with possible defaults and all.<br>
<br>
An important thing you need to know before you start on the raid is the rules by which the raid is lead. Know what the raid leader wants you to do ... most will preserve the /shout channel for instance to the Raid Leader and his assist, to the Main Assist and Secondary Assist when calling targets, and the puller to announce incoming targets. All other communication is usually done through /say or /ooc. Even then, some raid leaders may want people to use /ooc as minimal as possible, to cut down on the amount of messages being broadcast over the zone.<br>
<br>
Also, make sure you know what the rules are for loot. Often raid leaders will call one specific item to default to them (frankly, they deserve this for leading a raid is not anything easy to do), or something like that. Or, items to default to a specific class, like Red Dragon Scales for instance default to Warriors and Bards (they will be the only ones rolling on it then).<br>
<br>
Usually the rules I mentioned above are posted in the actual raid topic. Also, if you don't know what the rules are (many assume you know what the &quot;standard&quot; raid rules are), don't hesitate to ask - we all have/had to learn them at one given time, just like you would have to, now.<br>
<br>
The most important thing of all: LISTEN TO THE RAID LEADER! Failing to obey the orders he issues to keep the raid streamlined will guarantee you of a one way ticket out of the area sooner or later. Raid leaders will remember people who misbehave. They will also remember people who acted the way they liked, so if you are a &quot;good&quot; raider, you are more likely to receive a spot on a future raid that you sign up for.<br>
<br>
Expect raids to run between 4 (rather short) and 8 (somewhat long) hours usually, with the exception of single-monster raids, which are over when the monster in question is dead. Some raid can be longer - Plane of Air usually covers the entire weekend (with raiders sometimes logging off to get some sleep and log on once they are awake again).<br>
<br>
